Date: 10 Jul 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: SINAN, National Database of Notified Diseases, Brazil [edited]
<http://dtr2004.saude.gov.br/sinanweb/index.php?name=Fora>

In 2006, 83 cases of YF have been notified so far in Brazil.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The SINAN number refers to the number of notifications, but not of
confirmations. As yellow fever is such a sensitive issue, every case with
fever and icterus is notified as yellow fever. According to the system, if
you request any test for yellow fever in a public health laboratory,
filling a form for SINAN is mandatory. The number 83, therefore, is for
notified, or suspect cases. - Mod.LJS]
[According to the old International Health Regulations, suspected as well
as confirmed cases of YF in humans, primates or mosquitoes had to be
reported to WHO within 24 hours, with confirmation to follow as soon as
available. I cannot trace any report of these cases, confirmed or
suspected, on either the PAHO or WHO websites -- but maybe I didn't look in
the right place. I understand that the revised International Health
Regulations adopted by the World Health Assembly in May 2006 now allow WHO
to report outbreaks of internationally important diseases without having to
wait for official notification from the country. - Mod.JW]
